'''Ljubomir "Ljuba" Jezdić''' ({{lang-sr-cyr|Љубомир "Љуба" Јездић}}; October 1, 1884 — September 15, 1927), known by his ''[[nom de guerre]]'' '''Razvigora''' (Развигора<ref>Đurić & Mijović 1993, p. 97</ref>) was a [[Serbian Chetnik Organization|Serbian Chetnik]] ''[[voivode]]'' (military commander) in the [[Macedonian Struggle]], and a lawyer.<ref>МАТИЦА СРПСКА, СРПСКИ БИОГРАФСКИ РЕЧНИК, Азбучник, [http://www.maticasrpska.org.rs/biografije/tom04.pdf IV том, И - Ка] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120315164646/http://www.maticasrpska.org.rs/biografije/tom04.pdf |date=2012-03-15 }}, p. 35</ref><ref name=NESHS>Народна енциклопедија српско-хрватско-словеначка, Београд 1929, књига 2, 159.</ref>

==Life==

===Early life===
Jezdić was born in [[Loznica]], [[Kingdom of Serbia]] (western [[Serbia]]) on October 1, 1884.<ref name=NESHS/> The Loznica Jezdići live in [[Donja Badanja]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.poreklo.rs/2014/04/16/poreklo-prezimena-selo-donja-badanja-loznica}}/</ref> and [[Brnjac]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.poreklo.rs/2014/04/06/poreklo-prezimena-selo-brnjac-loznica}}/</ref> He finished six grades in the [[Šabac]] gymnasium, then entered the [[Military Academy (Serbia)|Serbian Military Academy]], but he was forced to cancel his studies before the end of the third year.<ref name=NESHS/> He then entered the [[Law School in Belgrade]], a period when he became one of the notable nationalistic youth leaders.<ref name=NESHS/> He was a fellow student with [[Dušan Dimitrijević]], a future [[wiktionary:brother-in-arms|brother-in-arms]].<ref>Glas Javnosti, Srpski četnici na početku dvadesetog veka (5), [http://arhiva.glas-javnosti.rs/arhiva/2003/03/03/srpski/F03030202.shtml Prvi gorski štabovi], 3. 3. 2003</ref>

===Chetnik action (1903–08)===
He had joined the [[Serbian Chetnik Organization]] and later crossed the Serbian-Ottoman border and entered Old Serbia on February 1, 1905, joining the band (''[[cheta]]'') of ''vojvoda'' [[Đorđe Ristić]].<ref name=NESHS/> He then made transfer to the band of Rista Starački. When Starački's was wounded in the hand fighting in Drenak and went and vacated in Serbia, Jezdić became the ''vojvoda'' of this unit.<ref name=NESHS/> He adopted the war name ''Razvigora'', due to the first warm springtime wind, which made the leaves sprout (from ''razvitak'', "sprout" and ''gora'', "forest").<ref>Krakov 2009, p. 176 {{quote|За њима су стизали и остали другови. Међу првим Љуба Нешић, Љуба Јездић правник и бивши питомац Војне Академије и Љуба Јовановић-Чупа, који су прешли са Ђорђем Скопљанцем. Рањен у руку на Дренку, Ђорђе се вратио у Србију, а Љуба Јездић је његову чету повео. По првом топлом пролетњем ветру, под којим се лишће развија понео је ново, војводско име Развогора.}}</ref> He participated in the great battle with the Ottoman army at [[Tchelopek|Čelopek]] (April 16, 1905).
 [[File:Cheta of Đorđe Ristić-Skopljanče.jpg|thumb|Serbian Chetnik Vojvoda [[Đorđe Ristić Skopljanče]] and his četa. Skopljanče in the centre, other notables in the photo include Ljuba Jezdić in the top row, third from the left, and [[Vojin Popović|Vojin Popović-Vojvoda Vuk]] next to him. Photo taken in 1905.]]
On 28 April 1905, the larger Kragujevac- and Belgrade bands arrived at the [[Dubočica]] village, led by [[Borko Paštrović]] and [[Aksentije Bacetović]] respectively.<ref name=GJ-Ubistvo_popa_Taska>Glas Javnosti, Srpski četnici na početku dvadesetog veka (7), [http://arhiva.glas-javnosti.rs/arhiva/2003/03/05/srpski/F03030402.shtml Ubistvo popa Taška], 5. 3. 2003</ref> [[Ilija Jovanović]], [[Lazar Kujundžić]], [[Pavle Mladenović]] and Ljuba Jezdić awaited them with their bands.<ref name=GJ-Ubistvo_popa_Taska/>

===Balkan Wars and First World War (1912–18) ===

He was a sergeant during the [[Balkan Wars]], and in the [[First World War]] he was a band commander, and commander of machine gunners in the Yugoslav volunteer regiment. After he fell sick, he was appointed a military delegate in [[Tunisia]]. He lived in [[Belgrade]] since 1918, working as a [[lawyer]], and died there on September 15, 1927.

